Date:    Wed, 18 Mar 92 08:35:42 -0500
From:    Brian Seborg <seborg@brutus.ncsl.nist.gov>
Subject: Michelangelo (PC)

In the March 16 Virus-L Otto Stolz asks the question: how can a
computer be booted after the double infection of first Stoned and then
Michelangelo.  I believe this was a rhetorical question in that Otto
has already figured out that it can't be.  In fact, this is where the
virus actually gives itself away in that the hard disk is no longer
bootable after a double infection.  In the scenario that I proposed:
first the Stoned infects a machine moving the MBR to sector 7 (at this
point the machine is still bootable), then the Michelangelo infects
the machine (copying the Stoned to sector 7 since it thinks it is the
MBR) now the machine is no longer bootable.  In both Viruses, however,
the partition table is not destroyed, only the partition program is
ovover written so the disk is still recoverable.  Also, the FAT table
is still intact and even if the partition table is destroyed it can be
reconstructed by physical ly lookin on the disk for the tell-tale
markers used to designate the beginning of a partition.  On my
collegues computer which was infected in this manner, it became
non-bootable and this is what alerted the user that something was
wrong.  Several antivirus packages were used to clean the disk, but
only NAV was able to actually clean the disk and reconstruct the MBR
and partition table.  That is not to say that all packages were tried,
but I know that a version of McAfee and CPAV were used to no avail.

Brian

