From:    mathews@kong.gsfc.nasa.gov (Jason Mathews - 514)
Subject: Re: New Virus? (PC)

quinonec@craft.camp.clarkson.edu (Q) writes:
>	 I found some of my .com files with odd dates on them, like
>00-02-80, 10-02-80, 00-00-00.  Anyways they grew some, and the
>appended code included the string "The Troi Virus".  Anyways, for no
>particular reason I decided to run scanv86b, and it didn't come up
>with anything.  I've looked at virx19, fp-202d and neither of them
>found it.
>	I was hoping someone would know a little something about it,
>ie what it does, and how to get rid of it.  Really appreciate any info
>as I don't want to turn on my computer unecessarily untill I get rid
>of it.

Here are some observations on the Troi Virus. I hope this can help you
deal with it.  Since it is a new virus, I suugest that you identify
the infected files and replace them with clean copies from a backup.

- --
Virus Name:	TROI VIRUS
Discovered:	March, 1992
Symptoms:	.COM file growth; file date/time change; TSR
Isolated:	United States
Eff Length:	322-324 bytes
Type Code:	PRsC - Parasitic Resident .COM Infector
Detection Method:	Scan for string "The Troi Virus"
Removal Instructions:	Delete infected files

General Comments:

The Troi virus was received from Colorado in March 1992.  Troi is a
memory resident infector of .COM programs.  When the first Troi
infected program is executed, the Troi virus will install itself
memory resident as a low system memory TSR.  It will have hooked
interrupt 21.	Once Troi is memory resident, it will infect .COM
programs when they are executed.

Virus easy to detect because it changes the times & dates for infected
files.  On 3/3/92 a file with the date 1-1-1992 was changed to
0-0-2048 and a file with the date 10-31-1989 was changed to 0-6-2045.
Approximately 56 years is added to infected files.  The virus probably
checks the date of a file before infecting it.

The virus requests 165 paragraphs when becoming resident.

Infects .COM files, but not those with the read-only attribute set.
Trying to infect a file on a write-protected disk will produce the
"Abort, Retry, Fail?" error message.

F-Prot V2.02D detects the virus with a heuristic search with the
following warning: Program contains several features which are
normally only found in virus programs.  It is almost certainly
virus-infected.  Scan V86B identified only one of the infected files
as the Best Wishes Virus.  The two viruses (Troi and Best Wish) have
similar characterics, but whether the two viruses are related is only
conjecture at this point.  The size differences between the two are
significant.

It is trully a new virus because no other virus protection program has
the signature for it.  However, programs monitoring disk activity,
such as writing to files, will trap the infection requests.

It does not look like the Troi virus does anything besides replicate.

