Date:    Wed, 18 Mar 92 09:05:51 -0500
From:    Brian Seborg <seborg@brutus.ncsl.nist.gov>
Subject: Bogus report of Michelangelo in Neural Networks and Fuzzy Systems (PC)

Gene Spaffords comments on potentially damaging reports of viruses on
diskettes distributed with books also pertains to bogus reports of
viruses on any type of software.  I would like to propose a method to
prevent further bogus reports and that is as follows:

	1) When you get a new diskette from any source, the first thing you
	 should do is write protect it, if it is not already write protected.
	 On 5 1/4" disks I keep a role of electrical tape (the cheap plastic
         type) so that I can cut off a small section for this purpose.  It
	 never falls off (unlike those cheap tabs provided with many diskettes).
	 For 3 1/2" disks I make sure the switch is set so that I can look
	 through the write protect hole.

The rationale for doing this first is simple, if you then insert them
(the disks) into an infected machine, they cannot become infected.

	2) Scan the diskettes with your favorite virus scanner.  If the disks
     	 are infected, then you know the source was either the retail store
	 (since many take returns and re-shrink-wrap the software without
	 scanning them for viruses) or it the source was the software producer.

If the PC comes up infected at this time, you know you got the virus
from somewhere else given that the diskettes check out clean.  You may
have to modify these procedures for diskettes containing compressed
files.  But you can do this by simply scanning your PC to ensure that
it is clean before performing step 2, or before performing the
decompression and installation of new software.

This method has the added value of ensuring that you have sound legal
footing if in fact the software does come to you infected in that you
can show that you have a standard procedure which ensures that you
were not the source of the virus.

Brian

