Date:    Wed, 18 Mar 92 09:28:59 -0500
From:    Brian Seborg <seborg@brutus.ncsl.nist.gov>
Subject: FDISK/MBR (PC)

In the March 16 Virus-L Michael Calanan asks whether FDISK/MBR can be
used in earlier versions of DOS.  My old Compaq MS-DOS version 3.3
manual in fact documents the use of FDISK/MBR for updating the MBR.
Therefore, I would imagine that this has been a feature of MS-DOS and
PC DOS since at least version 3.3.  No messages are given by this
command when it is invoked it only takes about a second or so to run,
and one is unsure that it has worked.  What I would suggest is to take
a computer you do not care about destroy the MBR by using Norton or
some other disk editor to write some bogus bits into it and then
attempt to use the FDISK/MBR program from whatever DOS version you
have.  My guess is that if you have version 3.3 or better this will
work resulting in your hard-disk becomming bootable again.

Let us know what happens.

Brian

