Date:    Wed, 18 Mar 92 10:49:29 -0500
From:    padgett@tccslr.dnet.mmc.com (A. Padgett Peterson)
Subject: MBRs & FDISK /MBR (PC)

Again, two questions on essentially the same subject

>From:    J.Verhage@cc.ruu.nl (Jaap Verhage)
>Subject: MBR-infectors, DOS 5 and FDISK /MBR (PC)

>Recently, in this group suggestions were made to use FDISK /MBR
>(undocumented) when using DOS 5 and being infected by a MBR-infector.
>I'm wondering: suppose you've partitioned your hard disk into multiple
>partitions, what then? I can't imagine FDISK being smart enough to go
>scan the disk all by itself, hunting for boot records or things like
>that, and making up the disk structure from that. Even worse: suppose
>you have a DOS- and a Unix partition?

There are actually two DOS 5.0 commands that can be used here. The first
is the undocumented FDISK /MBR (or my more powerful FixMBR for all OS
versions 8*). This replaces the executable code in the MBR only. It does
not change the partition table values hence there is no need to search the
disk.

The second is documented and a switch on the UNFORMAT command, /PARTN, that
restores the partition table only (not the executable code). Unless you know
exactly what you are doing, this can corrupt the table so I recommend using
only as UNFORMAT/PARTN/L/TEST. L tells it to List the current data and /TEST
tells it not to make any changes. Use DOS 5.0 "HELP UNFORMAT" or see the
manual for more information.

>From:    FRYSTD@ACAD.LVC.EDU (Michael Fry)
>Subject: Stoned/Michelangelo/etc overwriting partition (PC)

>2. Can it be relied on that FDISK or PART with newer DOS (like ver
>3,4,5) would start the partition later on the disk (18th logical
>sector is what seems more "normal", so sector 1 of head 1 of cylinder
>0)?  So re-paritioning might reliably prevent file damage by
>infection?

Starting a boot record  on an even track boundary became a specification
of DOS 3.0 and was incorporated into PC-DOS (IBM) and MS-DOS FDISK at that
time though some semi-custom versions of DOS were not updated until much
later. Disks that were FDSIKed with the early version may also still have
this format despite having been updated to a newer DOS. Note that sector 1
head 1 track 0 is not always the 18th sector (depends on disk structure).

					Warmly,

						Padgett

