Date:    18 Mar 92 12:36:43 -0500
From:    "David.M.Chess" <CHESS@YKTVMV.BITNET>
Subject: re: MBR-infectors, DOS 5 and FDISK /MBR (PC)

>From:    J.Verhage@cc.ruu.nl (Jaap Verhage)
>
>Recently, in this group suggestions were made to use FDISK /MBR
>(undocumented) when using DOS 5 and being infected by a MBR-infector.
>I'm wondering: suppose you've partitioned your hard disk into multiple
>partitions, what then? I can't imagine FDISK being smart enough to...

FDISK /MBR only replaces the *code* in the master boot record; it
leaves the existing partition table alone.  So as long as the
partition table correctly describes your current setup (the best way
to test this, as Bill Arnold suggested, is to cold-boot from floppy
and make sure the hard disk looks OK from there), it will still do so
after FDISK /MBR.  Regardless of whether the partitions are single or
multiple DOS or non, etc.

Remember, of course, that the option is undocumented, and therefore
unsupported, and you should have good backups *first*!

DC

